%N A394097 a(n) is the number of different ways for two particles to reach each other's starting corner on an equilateral triangular grid of side n units starting simultaneously and moving at the same constant speed along the grid lines, such that the distance between each particle and its own starting corner is always increasing, and the two particles never meet.
%C A394097 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. The x-axis is defined along AB and the y-axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A394097 A grid point (x,y) on a path of the moving point P satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path.
%C A394097 x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point.
%C A394097 Each of P path gives a unique Q path by transforming a grid point (h, k) on P path into (n-h-k, k) on Q path. A P path and a Q path do not meet if r-th coordinate of P is different from r-th coordinate of Q.The r-th and (r+1)-th coordinates of P must not appear swapped in Q at positions r and r+1.
%C A394097 Paths do not need to have equal length.
%H A394097 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a394/A394097.java">Java program</a> (github)
%e A394097 n = 2 has 4 different ways of reaching to other's starting corner:
%e A394097 Grid paths from A to B:
%e A394097  P1:{(0,0), (1,0), (2,0)},
%e A394097  P2:{(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A394097  P3:{(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)}.
%e A394097 Grid paths from B to A:
%e A394097  Q1:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A394097  Q2:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A394097  Q3:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,0)}.
%e A394097 Set of valid pairs of grid paths:
%e A394097  {(P1, Q2), (P2, Q1), (P2, Q3), (P3, Q2)}
%e A394097 Therefore a(2) = 4.
%Y A394097 Cf. A393796, A394098, A357603, A360444.
